    ```java
public String findLexSmallestString(String s, int a, int b) {
    int n = s.length();
    String minStr = s;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < 10; j++) {
            String rotatedStr = rotateString(s, b);
            String tempStr = addOdd(rotatedStr, a);
            minStr = minStr.compareTo(tempStr) < 0 ? minStr : tempStr;
            s = rotatedStr;
        }
        s = addAtIndex(s, a, n - i - 1);
    }
    return minStr;
}

private String rotateString(String s, int k) {
    k %= s.length();
    return s.substring(s.length() - k) + s.substring(0, s.length() - k);
}

private String addAtIndex(String s, int a, int index) {
    char[] arr = s.toCharArray();
    arr[index] = (char) ((arr[index] - '0' + a) % 10 + '0');
    return new String(arr);
}

private String addOdd(String s, int a) {
    StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(s);
    for (int i = 1; i < s.length(); i += 2) {
        sb.setCharAt(i, (char) ((s.charAt(i) - '0' + a) % 10 + '0'));
    }
    return sb.toString();
}
```

    1. Iterate for each position of the string.
2. In the inner loop, iterate 10 times to cover all possible sums of 'a' on odd positions.
3. In each iteration, apply the 'rotate' operation to the string, then apply the 'addOdd' operation to the string, and check if the resulting string is smaller than the current smallest string.
4. Outside the inner loop, apply the 'addAtIndex' operation to the original string to update the last even position by adding 'a' to it.
5. At the end of the outer loop, return the smallest string obtained.

The time complexity of this approach is O(n * 10 * (n + 10)), where n is the length of the input string s.
